solution.p:
As we have seen a few times, the matrix is
A=\left[\begin{array}{rr}
0 \amp -1 \\
1 \amp 0 \\
\end{array}\right]\text{.}

subsection.p:
We can develop a simple test to determine whether an n\times n lower triangular matrix is invertible. Let's use Gaussian elimination to find the reduced row echelon form of the lower triangular matrix
\begin{aligned} \left[\begin{array}{rrr} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 2 \amp -2 \amp 0 \\ -3 \amp 4 \amp -4 \\ \end{array}\right] \amp {}\sim{} \left[\begin{array}{rrr} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp -2 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 4 \amp -4 \\ \end{array}\right] \\ \amp {}\sim{} \left[\begin{array}{rrr} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp -2 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp -4 \\ \end{array}\right] \sim \left[\begin{array}{rrr} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ \end{array}\right]\text{.} \end{aligned}
Because the entries on the diagonal are nonzero, we find a pivot position in every row, which tells us that the matrix is invertible.

li.p:
Continuing with the Gaussian elimination algorithm, we have L_1 = R, as above,
L_2 = \left[\begin{array}{rrr} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\ \end{array}\right],~~~ L_3 = \left[\begin{array}{rrr} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \\ \end{array}\right]\text{.}
we then have L_3L_2L_1A = U.
